XXII

To F arco

You will not wonder Ι so strongly pressed you to confer the Tribunate upon my friend, when you shall be informed who and what he is; and as you have complied with my request, Ι may now acquaint you with his name and character. It is Cornelius Minicianus, who both in rank and character is the ornament of that province to which Ι owe my birth. His family and fortune are noble, and yet he pursues his profession with all the ardour of a poor man. He is a most upright juror, a most strenuous advocate, a most faithful friend. You will look upon the favour as conferred on yourself, when you shall have taken a nearer view of this excellent person,

who (not to speak in too lofty terms of so modest a man) is equal to all honours and titles that can be conferred upon him. Farewell.
